Malindi Sub-County Police Commander Joe Lekuta, who at first was reluctant to respond to the report, said they have launched investigations into allegations that the businessman was brutally beaten by police.
“He was found operating against the curfew hours and resisted arrest,” he told journalists.
However, Mr Kaibunga told journalists at Meridian Hospital, where he was admitted, that police accosted him while he was driving home at around 10.30pm.
“They later dragged me out of my car and began beating me up. They then bungled me into their van and robbed me of Sh105,000 cash which I had withdrawn to pay workers,” the trader said.





He said trouble started when he tried to plead with the officers to allow him to drive himself to the police station.
Roughed up
''I then made a phone call and immediately after making that call they roughed me up, holding my waist and dragged me towards the police land cruiser. I took my phone and put it inside the pocket,” he said.
He said the officers dragged him to the door of their van and as they lifted him his hand twisted and despite shouting in pain the officers pushed him into their vehicle.
''A female police officer who was in the team informed the deputy OCS that I had been injured. They drove with me leaving my vehicle open with its engine running and lights on,” he said.



