Mr Kaibunga said there were three other people in the van who had been arrested by the officers. He added that he refused to alight from the police vehicle, insisting that they take him to Malindi Sub-County Hospital.
X-ray examination
“After carrying out X-ray examinations which indicated that I had a fractured arm and the initial treatment, I was returned to the police station since I was under arrest,” he said.
He was later released on free bond and underwent surgery at Meridian Hospital where he incurred a Sh150,000 bill.
''I have been trying to follow up on my money which I was robbed by the police but they claim they are not aware of it,” he said.
Mr Phillip Matara, a Malindi activist, condemned the police brutality and wondered why the officers could not just arrest him and take him to the station then charge him in a court of law.
He said a similar incident occurred in Kisii where a youth lost his life to police brutality for allegedly flouting the curfew rule.
Mr Matara said Malindi is a tourist destination and its reputation should not be spoiled by a few rogue police officers who do not respect human rights.

slwanga@ke.nationmedia.com Interior CS Fred Matiang’i promises to release a report on the incident in three days. Irate civilians have been attacking police stations after officers use excessive force. The assaults come just before a tense general election due to take place Sunday. The cumulative tests in the country now stand at 1,029,748. Operations commander of Garbaharey confirms the killing of the militants.